      <title>24  Quadratic Forms (LN 2.2, 2.3)</title>
      <page>
        
        <p><m>\textbf{Poll Question}</m></p>
        <p>True or false: <m>Q(x,y) = 8x^2 +2y^2 - 8xy > 0</m> for all values of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.</p>
        <em>Hint: plot it in Desmos 3D! And: how does this exercise relate to symmetric matrices?</em>
      </page>
      <page>
        <p><m>{\large \textbf{Expressing Quadratic Forms in Terms of Symmetric Matrices}}</m></p>
        <p><m>\textbf{Definition}</m></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>A <b>quadratic form</b> is a function: <m>Q : \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}</m>, given by</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <me>
          Q(\vec{x}) = \vec{x}^T A \vec{x} =
          \begin{pmatrix}
            x_1 \amp x_2 \amp \ldots \amp x_n
          \end{pmatrix}
          \begin{pmatrix}
            a_{11} \amp a_{12} \amp \ldots \amp a_{1n} \\
            a_{12} \amp a_{22} \amp \ldots \amp a_{2n} \\
            \vdots \amp \vdots \amp \ddots \amp \vdots \\
            a_{1n} \amp a_{2n} \amp \ldots \amp a_{nn}
          \end{pmatrix}
          \begin{pmatrix}
            x_1 \\
            x_2 \\
            \vdots \\
            x_n
          \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>Matrix <m>A</m> is <m>n \times n</m> and symmetric, and <m>\vec{x}</m> is a variable vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>Example: express <m>Q = 3x_1^2 + x_2^2 + 8x_3^2 + 4x_1 x_2 - 6x_2 x_3</m> in the form <m>Q = x^T A x</m>.</p>
      </page>
      <page>
        <p><m>{\large \textbf{24.2  The Principle Axes Theorem}}</m></p>
        <p><m>\textbf{Theorem}</m></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>If <m>A</m> is a symmetric matrix then there exists an orthogonal change of variable <m>\vec{x} = P \vec{y}</m> that transforms <m>\vec{x}^T</m> to <m>\vec{y}^T D \vec{y}</m> with no cross-product terms.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p><em>Proof in the lecture videos/textbook</em></p>
        <p><m>\textbf {24.2.1  Example}</m></p>
        <p>Consider <m>Q = x^2 + y^2 + 2kxy</m> where <m>k \in \mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>Make a change of variable that transforms the quadratic form into another quadratic that has no cross-product terms.</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>For what values of <m>k</m> will <m>Q</m> satisfy <m>Q \ge 0</m> for any <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>?</p>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <em>Tip: it may help to plot the surfaces in Desmos 3D to see what the surface looks like as you change value of <m>k</m></em>
      </page>
      <page>
        <p><m>{\large \textbf{24.3  Classifying Quadratic Surfaces}}</m></p>
        <p>Our goal: <m>\textbf {solve optimization problems with quadratic functions}</m>.</p>
        <p>Take for example the surface:</p>
        <me>
          Q = x^2 + y^2 = \vec{x}^T
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp 1
          \end{pmatrix}
          \vec{x}
        </me>
        <p>If we set <m>Q</m> to be constant, <m>Q = k^2</m>, we obtain the equation of a circle whose radius is <m>k^2</m>.</p>
        <me>k^2 = x^2 + y^2</me>


