        <p>The surface above has a unique minimum at the origin. What about other surfaces?</p>
        <p><m>\textbf{Definition}</m></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>A quadratic form <m>Q</m> is</p>
            <ul>
              <li><p><m>\textbf{positive definite}</m> if <m>Q > 0</m> for all <m>\vec{x} \ne \vec{0}</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p><m>\textbf{negative definite}</m> if <m>Q > 0</m> for all <m>\vec{x} \ne \vec{0}</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p><m>\textbf{positive semidefinite}</m> if <m>Q \ge 0</m> for all <m>\vec{x}</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p><m>\textbf{negative semidefinite}</m> if <m>Q \le 0</m> for all <m>\vec{x}</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p><m>\textbf{indefinite}</m> when at least one eigenvalue is negative and at least one is positive.</p></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p><m>\textbf{Theorem}</m></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>If <m>A</m> is a symmetric matrix with eigenvalues <m>\lambda_i</m>, then <m>Q = \vec{x}^T A \vec{x}</m> is</p>
            <ul>
              <li><p><m>\textbf{positive definite}</m> when all eigenvalues are positive</p></li>
              <li><p><m>\textbf{negative definite}</m> when all eigenvalues are negative</p></li>
              <li><p><m>\textbf{indefinite}</m> when at least one eigenvalue is negative and at least one is positive</p></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </page>
